<div id="review_584788211" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/584788211" />
    <a title="K.A. Krisko" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7238959-k-a-krisko"><img alt="K.A. Krisko" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1350003280p2/7238959.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/584788211?book_show_action=true">Apr 08, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="K.A. Krisko" class="user" itemprop="url" name="K.A. Krisko" href="/user/show/7238959-k-a-krisko">K.A. Krisko</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7238959-k-a-krisko?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer584788211" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7552446248763967071">I read this twice in the last year. It has an interesting juxtaposition of biblical and philosophical argumentation with the author&apos;s experiences seeking information about his relatives who were lost in the holocaust in Poland. Thus, I learned a lot about Jewish culture and thought while I read, as well as being able to relate to the search. I particularly thought of this book in the summer of 2012, when my brother and I found the grave marker of a relative in a tiny, ancient cemetery in the Cze</span>
  <span id="freeText7552446248763967071" style="display:none">I read this twice in the last year. It has an interesting juxtaposition of biblical and philosophical argumentation with the author's experiences seeking information about his relatives who were lost in the holocaust in Poland. Thus, I learned a lot about Jewish culture and thought while I read, as well as being able to relate to the search. I particularly thought of this book in the summer of 2012, when my brother and I found the grave marker of a relative in a tiny, ancient cemetery in the Czech countryside, confirming for the first time the area in which our ancestors lived prior to WWII. The author's search reveals, bit by bit, the character and lives of his lost relatives; whenever it seems that he must be at the end, another bit of information keeps him searching a little bit longer, and yet another tiny piece is restored. This book serves as a kind of stand-in for those of us who will never be able to reconstruct the lives of our relatives as thoroughly. I've loaned it out now, but when I get it back, I'll read it again.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7552446248763967071" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


